requires: [sed]
run: run
provides: [run, sub, inplace, delete, print]
---

# sed

The streaming editor: read a file or stdin line by line, apply a script, emit to
stdout. `run` is the default; the rest are convenience entries over the common
scripts. The script language — addresses, commands, substitute flags, BRE vs
ERE — is in @text/sedlang; it mirrors vim's `:s`/`:g`, so see @vim/ex for the
in-editor twin and @vim/search for the regex. Reach for @search/rg instead when
you only want to *find* matches, not rewrite them, or want `.gitignore`-aware
recursion.

| Recipe | Script | Output |
|--------|--------|--------|
| `run` | your script | stream result to stdout |
| `sub` | `s/old/new/g` | every match replaced, to stdout |
| `inplace` | `s/old/new/g` with `-i` | rewrites the file (no stdout) |
| `delete` | `/pat/d` | drop lines matching `pat` |
| `print` | `-n '/pat/p'` | print only lines matching `pat` |

`run`, `sub`, `delete`, and `print` only stream — they never touch the file.
`inplace` is the one that writes: it edits the file with `sed -i` and prints
nothing. Patterns are BRE by default; pass an ERE script to `run` with a `-E`
flag baked into the recipe, or just write `\(\)`/`\+` the BRE way.

```just
# apply an arbitrary sed script to a file or stdin (default)
run script file="-":
  sed {{quote(script)}} -- {{quote(file)}}

# replace every occurrence of old with new, to stdout
sub old new file="-":
  #!/usr/bin/env sh
  set -eu
  o={{quote(old)}}; n={{quote(new)}}; f={{quote(file)}}
  sed "s/$o/$n/g" -- "$f"

# replace every occurrence in place, rewriting the file
inplace old new file:
  #!/usr/bin/env sh
  set -eu
  o={{quote(old)}}; n={{quote(new)}}; f={{quote(file)}}
  sed -i "s/$o/$n/g" -- "$f"

# delete every line matching a pattern, to stdout
delete pat file="-":
  #!/usr/bin/env sh
  set -eu
  p={{quote(pat)}}; f={{quote(file)}}
  sed "/$p/d" -- "$f"

# print only the lines matching a pattern
print pat file="-":
  #!/usr/bin/env sh
  set -eu
  p={{quote(pat)}}; f={{quote(file)}}
  sed -n "/$p/p" -- "$f"
```
